Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | API | Pattern | Replacement |
|----------|-----|---------|-------------|
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow + cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | Blocking wait | `Thread.Join(timeout)` |
| `ProcessLoop()` | `GetNextItem()` blocking | Blocking call | Must accept `CancellationToken` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // GetNextItem MUST accept a CancellationToken so it can
                // unblock when cancellation is requested. Without this,
                // cooperative cancellation stalls at the blocking call.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch block.
                // Clean up partial work, then let the loop exit naturally.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();  // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully.
        // Unlike Thread.Abort, this CANNOT force-stop the thread —
        // the thread must check the token and cooperate.
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. Log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in modern .NET.
            // If the thread is stuck in uncooperative code, you must
            // move that work to a child process and use Process.Kill.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept a `CancellationToken`.**
Your original comment says it "may block." If it blocks on a `Queue.Dequeue` or socket read, cancellation will never reach it. You must change it — for example, with `BlockingCollection<T>`:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework): blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could stop it
var item = _queue.Take();

// After (.NET 8): unblocks and throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
var item = _queue.Take(token);
```

**2. `Thread.ResetAbort()` has no equivalent — and none is needed.**
The old pattern was: abort injected → catch it → `ResetAbort` → loop continues. With cooperative cancellation, you simply *don't throw* — check `token.IsCancellationRequested` and `continue` or `break` as appropriate.

**3. There is no force-kill for threads in .NET 8.**
`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. If `GetNextItem()` hangs in uncooperative code (native call, third-party library), your only option is isolating it in a **child process** and calling `Process.Kill()`.

**4. Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`.**
It's `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks, especially if you ever use `CancelAfter`.

**5. `catch (OperationCanceledException)` uses a `when` filter.**
The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* cancellation — not an unrelated `OperationCanceledException` from library code.
